{"title": "Xiao Shuxuan\n", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xiao_Shuxuan", "tags": ["Category:1894 births", "Category:1945 deaths", "Category:Chinese collaborators with Imperial Japan", "Category:Chinese people of World War II", "Category:Generals from Fujian", "Category:Politicians from Fuzhou", "Category:Republic of China Army generals", "Category:Republic of China politicians from Fujian"], "text": "Xiao Shuxuan (Chinese: \u856d\u53d4\u5ba3; pinyin: Xi\u0101o Sh\u016bxu\u0101n; Wade\u2013Giles: Hsiao Shu-hs\u00fcan, 1894-1945) was a Chinese lieutenant general who served in the National Revolutionary Army before defecting to Wang Jingwei's Reorganized National Government of China. Xiao took part in the 1911 Xinhai Revolution and later fought in the Northern Expedition as a commander. In 1939-40, Xiao defected to Wang Jingwei's faction and joined his new pro-Japanese government. He held a number of prominent positions in Nanjing regime, including minister of Military Training and Chairman of the National Military Council. In 1943, when he was appointed head of the Central Military Academy and in March 1945, Army Minister.\nHe was killed in 1945 while resisting arrest.\n\nSources\nLiterature\nXu, Youchun. Dictionary of the People of the Republic (\u6c11\u56fd\u4eba\u7269\u5927\u8f9e\u5178 \u5897\u8a02\u7248). Hebei People's Publishing House, 2007. ISBN 978-7-202-03014-1.\nLiu, Shou. Official Chronology of the Republic of China (\u6c11\u56fd\u8077\u5b98\u5e74\u8868). Zhonghua Book Company, 1995. ISBN 7-101-01320-1.\n\n\n=== References ==="}